The paper discusses an algorithm for solving linear programs and non-linear problems, which suggests that it could belong to several sub-categories. However, the focus on violator spaces and their generalization of LP-type problems suggests that cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CG (Computational Geometry) are the most likely categories. The use of randomized algorithms and theoretical results also suggests cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). Finally, the paper may also be relevant to cs.CC (Computational Complexity) due to the discussion of algorithmic simplifications.
